shows.title: The should be a bank holiday show!
shows.description: Not so obvious 90s for today's Sunday Sunshine Social. Almost exclusively 90s britpop era indie and alternative, but not always the obvious tracks. Deeper cuts from early to late 90s as well as some nostalgic singalongs to balance things like a good pinch of salt! Perfect BBQ tunes!

shows.title: The unashamedly 80s show!
shows.description: More technical gremlins – courtesy of MixCloud this time – delayed today's show until the unusual hour of 3:45PM, so instead of being an early 80s-shake-off-the-cobwebs type of show, it was a bit more of a late afternoon (delight?) type of show. Some singalong epic ballads, some upbeat dancers and some rock as well. Nice!

shows.title: The Prince vibes (and birthday quiz) show!
shows.description: Initially planned to be a Prince themed fun funk show with some recognition of Caroline's birthday, this show features an impromptu 3 round 15 question music quiz leading into some requests from across the UK at dual parties! Fun times!! Warning, this show contains the word cunt. Possibly twice.

shows.title: The new blues show!
shows.description: Originally scheduled for Tuesday, today's show is a couple of days late due to some technical problems with the DJ software and Tidal which are thankfully now resolved! All new blues music released in the last year. Double-plays from each artist, from laid back and stripped down field recordings, to upbeat slickly produced tracks to dance to. This show pairs well with Cabernet Sauvignon and/or bourbon.

shows.title: The perfect hangover day tunes show!
shows.description: The plan for this show was to be able to sit back and swaddle ourselves in some nostalgic, comforting 90s alternative, but it seems the universe had other ideas, and either Tidal, djay Pro AI, or the rattler decided they didn't want to play the songs I selected, so this show was an improvised exploration of what the world really wanted to hear!

shows.title: The 80s soul, rock 'n roll show!
shows.description: Hugely inspired by the Tina Turner documentary "Tina!" on HBO Max (Sky Documentaries in the UK), I wanted to try to make up for underrating and under representing Tina Turner on the show so far. The documentary was a tough watch, but contained so much phenomenal footage of someone I now consider to be one of the greatest voices, and performers of all time. The 80s were a tricky time for a "sound"  - so much stuff was overproduced and the sense of people recording together was lost a little as digital multi-tracking reduced the need to get things right in fewer takes. With that said though, the 80s sound is also really great, so I wanted to play-through some contemporaries of the era and just enjoy the music.

shows.title: The deep dark 90s show!
shows.description: Following a few transatlantic beers together a week ago, Dave Tongue started pulling together a playlist of darker and moodier 90s songs, which is an excellent late night rabbit hole to descend into. Moving through several genres, but maintaining the overall vibe, the selections are eclectic, measured, and cathartic - the perfect thing to shake off the nonsense of the week.

shows.title: The most overlooked folk-rock LPs of the 1960s show!
shows.description: First thing I read this morning was a Rolling Stone article on Richard Thompson's new memoir Beeswing: Losing My Way and Finding My Voice. It tells a sad story of the fatal 1969 crash that killed the band's drummer Martin Lamble, and Thompson's girlfriend at the time Jeannie Franklin. The song I'll Keep It With Mine was played at Lamble's funeral. From here, I wanted to get into some of the deeper cuts of the folk-rock genre and found a superb article written by Richie Unterberger for Record Collector magazine in 2005. I played through some of the artists and built a playlist from here, and the show quickly evolved into a read-through of this article to accompany the selection of songs I had made. All credit to Richie Unterberger for this one!

shows.title: The new music show!
shows.description: After a few weeks away from the weekday shows it was great to dive back into the discovery of some new music. Quite eclectic, within the broad genre of rock and indie, today's show features new music from the last few weeks from newer and established artists.

shows.title: The Stanley's 60s and 70s rock and pop show!
shows.description: Ten year old Stanley Tongue curated today's show with some of his favourite tunes, in particular The Small Faces as he's a huge Steve Marriott fan! Pop, rock, psychedelic rock, folk and roots are all included - perfect for a lazy Sunday afternoon (which isn't on today's playlist 🤣).

shows.title: The sleazy, swaggering, slow ride of 60s and 70s heavy blues-rock show!
shows.description: Deeper cuts of well known bands from the era and the genre, including some recognition of Steven Tyler's 73rd birthday yesterday.

shows.title: The super 70s sunny road trip sounds show!
shows.description: Inspired by the vibe of yesterday's 38 Special track, today's show is built around that sound with songs mostly from 1978 - 1982ish (with a few exceptions). Well known bands, but deeper cuts. Fire up that V8, roll down the window, and get yourself a forearm tan to these tunes!

shows.title: The one year anniversary show!
shows.description: One year, what a year. This is the first playlist from a year ago. It's quite... eclectic, but it's really fun, and if you're occupying all your senses except your ears, why don't we share a little drinky together while we listen? Thank you for listening with me!

shows.title: The Sunday social show!
shows.description: Mother's Day in the UK, and Stefan's 40th birthday mean today's show is an eclectic mix of upbeat, danceable, singable, strutable songs! Thanks Stefan and Suzie for sharing some of your favourite songs, and thanks to everyone for the messages for Stefan! Happy 40th!

shows.title: The 1950s Rock & Roll, Rhythm & Blues show!
shows.description: After a few weeks break to move coasts, today I was inspired by some 1950s Rock & Roll, starting off with Eddie Cochran's C'Mon Everybody. Nothing too academic as I'm running off the mobile rig until the studio is setup again, but a play-through of fun, upbeat, danceable tunes!

shows.title: The (musical) Feast of Saint Valentine show!
shows.description: With love from around the world, Dave Tongue and I have curated something special for you on this 14th day of February. Whether you’re flying solo, or neck deep in affection, there’s sure to be something to tickle your fancy! Warning: This show contains the words "Wet Ass Pussy!" 😉

shows.title: The hard-rock, blues-rock, groove-rock, funk-rock show!
shows.description:
Slammin' Gladys released their new album Two yesterday and I listened to it so much I didn't do a show. I wanted to represent the music in a way that didn't just lazily tie it to the late wave of 80s rock bands washed away by the tsunami of grunge. Today's show is a play-through of that kind of blues-groove guitar driven music that hits hard and gets you air drumming, strutting, strumming, and singing along to the swagger.

*Also, to correct a misstatement I made in this show speaking about Richie Kotzen and his time with the band Poison. He did not have sex with the drummer and get fired. He had sex with the drummer's wife and got fired. An important distinction! ;)

shows.title: The supergroups show Pt. 2!
shows.description: Following on from yesterday's show, today we start in 1979 and listen through to the supergroups of the 1980s. A little louder, a little brighter, a little tighter, and a LOT more 80s. I think I was a little naive to think I could finish this journey in three shows. It's going to take a few more, and I'll spread them out across the next few weeks. More to come!

shows.title: The supergroups show!
shows.description: I love a supergroup. I mention it every time I play one, and I keep promising myself that I'll do a show about them! As it turns out, there are more than I even realised and so this show is just part one of what may be a three part show. There's something somehow slicker about a supergroup. Perhaps it's less pressure, perhaps it's more, but either way the players seem out to prove something and that's fine with me! Starting in 1960, this first show takes us up to 1977. More to come!

shows.title: The new music show!
shows.description: A little rock, a little indie, a little folk, a little pop - all seasoned with a salt bae pinch of metal! Today's show is particularly eclectic and features new music from established artists as well as new music from new artists. Special recognition to the band Psychedelic Porn Crumpets for superb name!

shows.title: The suitable Sunday sounds for your snow day show!
shows.description: Today's show is a play-through of 80s and 90s alternative, indie, post-punk, new wave, goth rock and Madchester tunes. If you're looking for that firm lingering hug of mildly melancholic music, this one might be for you! Now what's for Sunday dinner? Oh, and Happy Birthday Christine!

shows.title: The epic, symphonic, cinematic, post-rock, space-rock show!
shows.description: Today's show is an escapist soundscape perfect to drift off into. Heavy in places, but with enough balance throughout to not completely sonically overwhelm you. With artists from China, Sweden, Switzerland, Poland, Ireland, England and the US it's a veritable travelogue of tunes for your aural engagement. Likely pairs well with a Cabernet Sauvignon and some dark chocolate and perhaps a ripe taleggio!

shows.title: The perfect rocky Friday night getting ready show!
shows.description: I LOVE The Struts' new album Strange Days, and in particular the track Another Hit of Showmanship, and I'm always looking for a way to carry on that rocky, punchy, fun and funky vibe throughout a whole show. Since doing the new music shows on Tuesdays I've discovered so much new music and really caught up with what I've been missing out on over the past few years. So starting with The Struts, I began to build the playlist and to my great joy and amusement all the tracks I was picking were released in the last year, and many of the artists I've played on new music shows over the last 9 months or so. I pictured myself leaving work, heading to the local bar, loading the juke box up and sinking several strong beers to shake off the week. Cheers!

shows.title: The super, super, funky show!
shows.description: All credit for the playlist for today's show (apart from the last three songs) goes to Phil "Dr. Philphy" Edwards and his longtime friend and bandmate Steve Chandra Savale - currently of Asian Dub Foundation. Phil and Steve's history has been told a little bit on earlier shows, but Steve's love for funk, and deep cuts from the funk canon (nice job on the homonym English language!) is ready to take you on a musical voyage. There are some SERIOUSLY funky tracks on here so strap in, screw your wig on tight, and turn it up!

shows.title: The late 60s/early 70s British(ish) blues show!
shows.description: "Less shredding, more blues" was the direction received from my Dad to inform this show 🤣, along with a performance of Sugar Mama by Taste. From here I created a playlist of slower, more obscure, almost exclusively British blues tracks (genre not origin of course!), with a few era appropriate and vibe appropriate American bands in compliment! Sit back, unplug, pour yourself a whiskey, gin, cup of tea, or red wine, and sink back into the smooth, sultry, sound of these slow blues tracks.

shows.title: The new music show!
shows.description: What's new in 2021? Most of the tracks today are, with some revisits to albums by artists who released new music towards the end of 2020. A variety of genres are represented today, as are a variety of countries. Keep an ear out for the Seaford Mods track, and if the sound from a mouth "fuck" upsets you, well, perhaps you have the wrong radio station, but it is sung in repetition by a 70 year old man during the last track. Who are we to judge?! 🤘🏻

shows.title: The eclectic, international effort show!
shows.description: Starting with a playlist curated almost to completion by Dave and Stanley Tongue, that they starting working on after listening to a show a few weeks ago. I selected a few extra tracks to bring us up to time for this play-through across a number of genres, with songs primarily from the 90s and 00s. There's also a special treat for the more discerning listener of the show with a premiere of a track just re-discovered on an old MiniDisc from the Baron Tongue himself!

shows.title: The sometimes one isn't enough show!
shows.description: Some songs, on some albums are just made to be played consecutively - it's more than just random song order, it's great album design! Today's show is a double-play through of songs to sing along to, air drum along to, and headbang along to. Yesterday was my brother's birthday, and many of these albums from today's show I copied from him when I was still in single digits. What beats a little 80s rock on a Saturday night. A LOT of 80s rock on a Saturday night!

shows.title: The United States musical travelogue show!
shows.description: Today's show was an alphabetical, autobiographical travelogue through the states I've lived in and visited. The rules were the songs had to have the State name in them, and for places I've lived I went a little deeper with some more songs with more geographical and biographical detail. From Dolly to Dylan, Ben Folds to Bill Monroe, Bloodhound Gang to Bill Withers, Elvis to Ellington, the music is as eclectic as all the places I've been lucky enough to see!

shows.title: The what makes bass players tick show!
shows.description: Dan Finn has put together a playlist of tracks that have inspired himself and fellow Hastings, East Sussex bass players over the years! To pick or not to pick. To slap or not to slap. Four strings or more? Slap like now!

shows.title: The Steve Lillywhite show!
shows.description: Finally getting a chance to have a play-through of some of Steve Lillywhite's work. Punchy, punky, rocky, funky, slick, sparkling and sweet! Steve Lillywhite's career began in the early 1970s where he was a tape operator for Polygram. He was soon producing and contributing to some of the most well known and successful music of the following decades and continues to produce today having been awarded six Grammy awards and a CBE!

shows.title: The eclectic, energetic, indulgent, punky, funky, alternative show!
shows.description: Beginning with a playlist that Dave and I put together at the start of the new year for another two presenter show that sadly never happened, today's show is upbeat, fun, and wanders through a number of genres. Criteria for tracks? Generally punchy, well-produced or in some other way urgent and interesting!

shows.title: The sleepy Saturday 70s and 80s rock/pop/funk vibes show!
shows.description: Originally playlisted for last week, this show is full of gentle yet considered tracks that occasionally bust out some serious grooves and funk. Great singalong backing vocals throughout and something to add a little sparkly to a sleepy Saturday evening.

shows.title: The New Year's Eve (and 200th show) show!
shows.description: Just some fun songs across a number of decades and genres as a pre-show for your New Year's Eve plans. Some dancers, some singers, some screamers and some crooners. Everything you should need really! Thanks for listening with me!

shows.title: The new music guest presenter show!
shows.description: Today's show introduces a new voice to the show with long-time, long-distance contributor "Dave" to the guest presenter mic. We explore some new releases across a variety of genres and play out a track to push for Brexit Number 1 by Asian Dub Foundation and Stewart Lee.

shows.title: The most played of the year show!
shows.description: A retrospective of the most played tracks from the year as we approach the end of the year, and the 200th show! Selections from the 60s, 70s, 80s, 90s, 00s, 10s, and 20s! Thanks for listening with me.

shows.title: The mellow fireside folk show!
shows.description: Inspired by an article I was reading about Topic Records, today's show is a play through of primarily British folk singer-songwriters from the early 1960s to present day. Mellow, laid back, and a perfect pairing for a wet and windy Christmas Eve Eve. Grab yourself a cloudy cider, or a mulled wine and sink back into it.

shows.title: The new music show!
shows.description: More new music recently released and from the last year. I've really grown to enjoy doing these new music shows and discovering new material from a variety of artists. Today's oldest is Paul McCartney at 78, the youngest...? I'm not actually sure! As always, I don't play edited versions of songs, and some of the songs (and commentary) contain the words fuck, shit, anus, and cunt. Big hugs everyone, they're just mouth noises, and they only make sense to English speaking listeners.

shows.title: The little bit 70s, little bit 90s show!
shows.description: Building from a collaborative playlist with Dave that we pulled together last night, this show starts out with some 70s rock/blues-rock and transitions into some 90s indie/alternative/britpop, but mostly deeper cuts!

shows.title: The little soul, little R&B, little indie/alternative show!
shows.description: Inspired by a conversation about a late friend's CD collection, today's show starts with an album track from Macy Gray and then moves through that vibe and genre. Soulful, lush vocals, epic arrangements. Something for everyone.

shows.title: The synth-poppy, new-wavey, art-rocky, pop show!
shows.description: Matching the vibe that the rainy weather has delivered this morning, today's show plays through some of the more melancholy music of the 80s pop canon, before manoeuvring into some more upbeat pop-rock to close out. A little bit escapist, a little bit introspective, but plenty to sing along or dance to too. Everything is going to be ok.

shows.title: The simply Soulful Saturday sixties show!
shows.description: It's been a few weeks without some real Soul on the show, and that felt like too long! Today's show is more about the Soul vibe than a specific story about STAX, Motown, or even Northern Soul. Nothing too academic, just great songs moving through a number of vibes - upbeat, funky, danceable, slow, smooth and always soulful.

shows.title: The new music show!
shows.description: Originally planned for Tuesday, today's show is a play through of new music recently released, and going back through the months. A little rockier in vibe today, but nothing too scary!

shows.title: The (mostly) 70s rock, funk and pop show!
shows.description: Beginning yesterday with the assertion that Vivaldi is the Bryan Adams of Classical music, I entered into a conversation with Giles who made a strong case for it being Robert Palmer instead. Today's show begins with a Robert Palmer track and walks an at times funky, rocky and poppy road, but doesn't perhaps complete the conversation about Vivaldi. What do you think?

shows.title: The eclectic, immersive, escapist show!
shows.description: Moving through a few genres and vibes, today's show starts off quite eclectic with some 60s and 70s rock, blues-rock, and psychedelic rock. It then moves into some more immersive and theatrical progressive, yet accessible tracks, before settling into the escapism of 70s and 80s glam/pop/rock.

shows.title: The new music show!
shows.description: Another dive into new music mostly released in the last few weeks across a variety of sub-genres that nestle comfortably under the broader umbrella genres of pop, rock, and alternative. Great new tracks from Phoebe Bridgers, Whitney Tai, Yarnell, Soccer Mommy (thanks for the new sting mid-show Daniel), and The Brummies, but plenty for everyone with a critical and curious ear!

shows.title: The blues rocky, power-poppy, post-punky, new wavey solid Sunday show!
shows.description: Sunday, November 29th, 2020 - the blues rocky, power-poppy, post-punky, new wavey solid Sunday tunes show! Inspired by the Glastonbury performance of Can't You Hear Me Knocking by The Rolling Stones, today's show starts out with a riff and a vibe, and moves through a number of genres that you can let envelop you. From power bass lines to thundering (yet subtle) drums, and epic vocal performances, this is a show for a glass or two of wine and a roast dinner!

shows.title: The smooth, mellow, funky soul show!
shows.description: Slow, funky (slunky?) tunes to sink into and nod your head too. I woke up thinking about a 1970s vibe, and this playlist delivered itself to me shortly thereafter!

shows.title: The music from 80s movies show!
shows.description: I love a good movie soundtrack, and I think some of the best movies, and best movie soundtracks came from the 80s. This show has made me want to watch all of these movies in this order!

shows.title: The needed some more nineties show!
shows.description: Listening to that 90s production in yesterday's show, I needed a little more today. So cozy up in a cuddle puddle of nostalgia, slip on a knit, slide into some bootcut jeans, crack a couple of beers and turn it up!

shows.title: The mostly 90s rock/alternative show!
shows.description: Buckcherry have been on my mind the last few days, so today's show is bookended with them with a variety of mostly 90s rock in between, straying briefly and appropriately into the 80s and 00s when necessary. And it's always necessary!

shows.title: The bluesy Tuesday show!
shows.description: With a little rain creeping in to really seal the end of summer in California, today felt like the right day to play some blues. John Mayall, Eric Clapton, Peter Green, Taj Mahal, and Buddy Guy are a few of the artists featured, inspired by a recommendation from my Dad to play the Jeff Beck track Morning Dew.

shows.title: The nineties were female show!
shows.description: I was in the mood for a nineties show this morning, and started off programming with Elastica. Then Sleeper. Then Catatonia, and then I realised, that's what the theme needs to be - 90s female fronted (or all female) bands!

shows.title: The more mellow multi-decade folk-rock show!
shows.description: My Dad shared a Fairport Convention track with me earlier in the week, and I asked him to follow it up with some songs of a similar vibe. Today's show is that playlist! Music from the 60s through to the 00s that you can sink back into and escape with.

shows.title: The mostly new music from mostly established artists show!
shows.description: Being Friday and all, it felt like the right time to get back to a little rock! More of a vibe-show today, than a strict theme, but as it shakes out, most of the music is new from 2020, from artists and bands that have been around for some time! Keep an ear out for the Morrissey track, it's excellent!

shows.title: The nineties and noughties hip hop and rap show!
shows.description: Apologies for using the term "noughties" but the alliteration was too strong to resist.  I haven't got to play much of this genre on the show yet, but I LOVE it, even though I'm probably only slightly more knowledgeable on this than Jazz... Join me in an exploration, and grab a gin & juice!

shows.title: The classic “Classic Rock” for road-trippin’ or tea-sippin’ show!
shows.description: Wrap yourself up in the warmth of these smooth Sunday sounds, and drift away in the luscious production of some gorgeous classic rock. Perfect for a road trip, or even an afternoon cup of tea. Your choice - as is everything!

shows.title: The mostly not about the election result show!
shows.description: Inspired by The Strut's new album - Strange Days, today's show is all new music from the last 6-8 weeks, with the exception of a few "result appropriate" tunes to bid farewell to the current occupant of 1600 Pennsylvania Avenue!

shows.title: The mostly mellow, mostly 80s show!
shows.description: Originally programmed as a distraction for US Election night, I decided to save this show of deeper, calmer cuts until today. England just entered lockdown again, and who knows what's happening in the US?! If you need something to lower your cortisol levels, this show might be it, and I only mentioned the election twice I think. ❤️

shows.title: The Halloween show!
shows.description: Starting off with 30 minutes of 90s alternative (to make sure the streaming issues I've been having weren't still "creeping" around), the show today was all Halloween related music. Jellyfish, Alice Cooper, The Zombies, The Specials... You get the idea! 🧟‍♂️🧟‍♀️🎃

shows.title: The new wave, new romantic show!
shows.description: I don't recall exactly where the inspiration came from for this this morning, but I was in the mood for some more 80s songs, as I think it's a decade I've neglected a little. I went a bit off-piste after Scritti Politti, but only to include more fun upbeat sizzlingly produced tracks before returning to the playlist.

shows.title: The new music show!
shows.description: A play-through of new music released in the last couple of weeks. The majority of which falls within the broad genre of "rock" but as always, there is some variance!

shows.title: The moodier music from the 80s show!
shows.description: Nothing too deep and moody, but a playlist trying to avoid some of the more obvious clichés, while still enjoying the overall sound of the decade. Some rock, some pop, some hip-hop/rap, and some glorious "alternative."

shows.title: The newer music from older(ish) artists show!
shows.description: Starting out with brand new music from Bruce Springsteen, I wanted to explore the most recent music from a variety of bands, musicians, and artists that I've listened to over the years. Focusing more on the overall vibe of the music, rather than specific genres, today's show is a play-through of Aerosmith to AC/DC, The Cars to Counting Crows, and The Rolling Stones to Richard Thompson - there should be something for everyone!

shows.title: The Carol Kaye show!
shows.description: Carol Kaye is one of the most prolific recorded bass guitarists in rock and pop music, playing on an estimated 10,000 recordings in a career spanning over 50 years. She features heavily in the 2008 documentary The Wrecking Crew, and she is very likely the bass player that you never knew you knew. Today's show is a play-through of some of the contributions that she has made as a musician to popular music throughout the decades.

shows.title: The Spencer Davis inspired show!
shows.description: Sadly, the inspiration for this show began with another obituary, as Spencer Davis died earlier this week. Today is a play-through of some of his music and the music of his contemporaries, exploring the sound of blue eyed soul and psychedelic 60s rock.

shows.title: The new music show!
shows.description: Reflecting on and revisiting some of the new music I've discovered over the past few months, today's show also includes some brand new music from artists such as Bruce Springsteen, The Waterboys, Sturgill Simpson, and Cee-Lo Green.

shows.title: The results of yesterday’s record shopping show!
shows.description: I picked up some great records yesterday, expanding my collection of Traffic and Steve Winwood, and adding some more Richie Havens, Cream and a clean copy of Buckingham Nicks. Today's show is a little laid back, lightly proggy, somewhat bluesy, and occasionally funky. Perfect Sunday listening 😎

shows.title: The inspired by Empire Records show!
shows.description: I just re-watched a favourite movie again a few nights ago - Empire Records - and inspired by its soundtrack of moody, irreverent, fun, 90s alternative rock, pop, and grunge I took a leap into a neverland of nostalgia with some tracks that wouldn't have sounded out of place playing in the store! It's not Rex Manning day, but that doesn't mean you can't get excited anyway!

shows.title: The Northern Soul show!
shows.description: Adrian Tongue (Adrian Andrews!) has curated a superb playlist for today’s show, of Northern Soul classics, paying tribute to the top DJ of the era Kevin Roberts, while also taking himself back to his time as a DJ at Club Rex amongst others, spinning some of these classics himself! Keep The Faith ✊🏻

shows.title: The coolness test (sort-of) show!
shows.description: Are you as cool as a five year old? Today started with some of Rufus Tongue’s favourite songs (he turned 5 yesterday!) and then moved through some requests to accommodate a party I'm sadly missing while on the wrong continent. Upbeat, fun, and across several decades.

shows.title: The music needn’t take itself so seriously show!
shows.description: Tenacious D caught my eye and ear this morning, and that's all it took to put me in the mood for some silly, fun, mostly early 2000s rock. It's also Rufus Tongue's birthday today, and this show is entirely inappropriate for a 5 year old. Except Rufus isn't just any 5 year old!

shows.title: The smoooooooth 70s sounds show!
shows.description: Dr. Phil "Musical Coming of Age shows" Edwards inspired me again this morning by sending me a video of a version of Baker Street that we performed a few years ago as part of the band Bloody Holly. That set me off on a 70s rock vibe. Thanks Phil!

shows.title: The Eddie Van Halen show!
shows.description: I found myself as shocked and saddened as many guitarists, and music lovers seemed to be at the news that Eddie Van Halen died yesterday. Today's show was an insight into his influences and an example of his style, based on an article I read about him in Rolling Stone from a few years ago. Starting right at the beginning with Les Paul, speaking to his admiration for Eric Clapton, and gathering together all of the ingredients that came together to make him the musician he was.

shows.title: The new music show!
shows.description: I've missed playing new releases, while I've been digging deeper into music that's new to me, so I had a listen to some new stuff released over the last six weeks or so that fits within the broad genres and vibes that I enjoy.

shows.title: The Adrian Tongue birthday Motown show!
shows.description: In years past we've formed bands and played some of Adrian's favourite songs for him live, but this year for all the reasons, things are a little different. I've heard Adrian talk about Motown more than any other label, and I've enjoyed the introduction to many artists from him, so today is a little something in return. Hits from Hittsville, a play-through of some of the biggest songs from the first decade of Motown. Happy Birthday Adrian!

shows.title: The Point Break Radio Live Music Festival show!
shows.description: If we can't make it to see music live in person, then the next best thing is a fantasy live music festival. Get your wellies and your toilet roll, your cans of Stella, flags and bucket hats, and sit back into your deck chair and enjoy some live performances!

shows.title: The 80s/90s rock show!
shows.description: I don't imagine that there were many people that had a dream about Enuff Z'Nuff last night, but I did, and I was listening to a tape of their album Strength. That was all the inspiration I needed for today's show when I woke up, but I thought I'd explore some more un-listened (for me) territory within this genre and these years. Nothing too obscure, and it was a great way for me to shake off the work week. Grab your cowboy boots. Let's rock!

shows.title: The post-punk era show!
shows.description: Dr. Philphy of "Phil's musical coming of age fame" sent me an XTC video that I woke up to this morning, and that inspired today's show. I loved the introduction he game me to XTC with tracks such as Respectable Street from his early musical autobiography shows, and really enjoyed the opportunity to pull together a list of tunes from that era that meander across a few genres of that time.

shows.title: The alt-ish, indie-ish, inspired by Ben Folds show!
shows.description: Still somewhat inspired by finishing Ben Folds' book, I'm finding myself wanting to listen to a lot of his music. However, the licensing terms of MixCloud mean that I can't just play endless Ben Folds, so today I started and finished with him and pulled together a musical journey in-between!

shows.title: The math-rock, metal-core, post-rock, dream-prog show!
shows.description: Again, inspired by a Davie504 video (look him up on YouTube), I found my way to a band called Polyphia, and built a playlist from there. Brilliant and somewhat challenging music, but melodic, and thoughtful too. Give it a try, you might like it!

shows.title: The piano in rock and pop show!
shows.description: I just finished Ben Folds' autobiography "A Dream About Lightning Bugs: A Life of Music and Cheap Lessons" and it was superb! Ben Folds has been a favourite artist of mine since the first album, and although I can't just do a Ben Folds show (sadly), I wanted to try out a show where piano is featured in all of the songs. Upbeat, fun, a little irreverent at times, and very Ben Folds-y. Today's show proves that pianos rock!

shows.title: The funking funky as funk show!
shows.description: Quite fortuitously, I happened upon a highly amusing YouTuber called Davie504 this week, and that was all it took to inspire a super funky, bass heavy show. That and watching Mallrats last night! Strap in, turn it up, and get ready for maximum SLAPP! This was also the 150th show!

shows.title: The family affair show!
shows.description: Father and son Adrian and Dave Tongue collaborated to curate today's playlist, and it's a journey through rock and pop from the early 1960s to the 1990s. Poppy, rocky, psychedelic, upbeat and happy, with just a few moody and sinister tracks in there too.

shows.title: The Nile Rodgers show Pt. 2!
shows.description: I've been getting deep into the Nile Rodgers autobiography Le Freak, and it's fantastic! It's a brilliant snapshot of New York in the 60s, 70s, and 80s, with enough detail to jog my memory of living there, and inspire me to add a few new places to explore and walk amongst the ghosts of music history next time I'm there. Nile Rodgers has written, composed, produced, played (and been sampled on) some of the best music over the last five decades, and some of my all time favourite tracks. He's a true pop music superstar. Starting off with some late 60s and early 70s (non Nile Rodgers) tracks that have been playing in my head over the past week, today's show takes a wander through the music that Nile Rodgers has created over the first three decades of his career.

shows.title: The Tamarin time machine birthday show!
shows.description: I found an old set list from a band I was in around 2000-2002 called Tamarin. It was a Boxing Day (the day after Christmas) show, and at that time we were playing 3 or 4 times a week as a tiny power-duo. There's some good stuff on the setlist, and great memories hearing it back again. A little bit self-indulgent, but it is my birthday :) (These are the originals, not the covers we did!)

shows.title: The Suzie and Stefan's 10 year anniversary show!
shows.description: My excellent and long, long time friends Suzie and her husband Stefan are celebrating their 10th wedding anniversary today, but instead of giving them tin, we've given them rock!

shows.title: The jump blues boogie woogie show!
shows.description: Inspired by a rabbit hole I went down during yesterday's show, today is a play-through of some swinging jump blues, boogie woogie and rockabilly.

shows.title: The more melancholy and moody life on Mars show!
shows.description: Living under the strange sepia and orange hue of the California wild fires, amidst its eery day-long dusk, inspired a slightly more melancholic playlist today with longer form songs, to disappear into. All is well, but all is unusual.

shows.title: The 21st century rock show, Pt. 2!
shows.description: I really enjoyed yesterday's show, so I thought I'd continue the theme. Starts off a little heavier, and then moves through some mildly mellow, but generally maintains the upbeat assertiveness of 2000s rock. This one will also sound good loud in the car, particularly if you have a longer road trip!

shows.title: The 21st century rock show!
shows.description: I woke up with The Raconteurs' Steady, as She Goes in my head, and the setlist snowballed from there. All post-2000 rock, with some indie, and alternative in there too. This one will sound good loud in the car!

shows.title: The summery September Sunday sounds show!
shows.description: It's forecast to hit 107 degrees today on this long labo(u)r day weekend. Today's show is a play-through of summer songs from as early as 1935 to 2001 across a number of genres. Sit back, stay cool, and enjoy the summer.

shows.title: The stretching out the summer with some songs that “slap” show!
shows.description: Funky, bluesy, rocky, these songs have swagger, and mixed with a late summer afternoon, should sound perfect with your BBQs, picnics, road-trips or beach day!

shows.title: The sounds of a sixteen year old’s mixtape show!
shows.description: We've had musical coming of age shows, biographical shows, autobiographical shows, but today's show taps directly in to fresh ears in an almost endless universe of music. Madeline Alemi has expertly curated a playlist for today's show based on her experience making proper (cassette) mix-tapes for herself and her friends, and has shared some of her favourite tracks in a mix tape she's called "the ultimate show!"

shows.title: The 1979 show!
shows.description: I've been waiting for an opportunity to play Prince again, and in particular the 1979 version of "I Could Never Take the Place Of Your Man." Instead of just compiling a playlist from that point, I decided to have a listen to what was popular across a variety of genres from that year, and go on a little musical excursion into the past.

shows.title: The 90s grunge-ish alternative rock-ish show!
shows.description: I've had the opening track from Live playing in my head for the last few days, so today's show was an opportunity to exorcise (and maybe even exercise 🏋🏻‍♂️) that demon! 😈 A play-through of 90s alt, grunge, and indie tunes settling into some gentler more melodic singalongs towards the end.

shows.title: The selections from 68 & 69 show!
shows.description: I just started watching the documentary "Woodstock: 3 Days of Peace & Music." Spoiler alert: It's excellent! In a similar way to how I felt affected by the documentary Laurel Canyon, I found it humanised an event that has been elevated to such a level that made it feel inaccessible in some ways. For today's show I wanted to listen to and explore what was happening in rock music around the time of Woodstock, and consider what music may have been playing on the tape decks of the cars of the people that travelled there.

shows.title: The swinging 6/8 summer Sunday show!
shows.description: With a caution to not approach this too academically, this is a show, where the music isn't in 4/4 time. 6/8 has a lovely swing to it, and just makes you want to move. Today is a play-through of songs you feel in 3! If I hadn't mentioned it, you might not have noticed, so just ignore me and swing away!

shows.title: The something for everyone summer Saturday show!
shows.description: Starting off with a little reggae courtesy of Bob Marley, and then moving through some sweet selections of pristine 80s pop (Nile Rodgers is back!), before descending into some alternative, then traversing through some classic guitar tunes, and settling into some classic blues. Join us on the journey!

shows.title: The conscience of country show!
shows.description: Inspired by an article I read this morning called The Conscience of Country by Tom Moon in Tidal magazine, today's show is a play-through of music from a genre where "...pushing back against injustice has been as essential as Jack Daniel’s, pickup trucks and mama."

shows.title: The mellow, mildly melancholic, soothing soundscapes show!
shows.description: With quite a change of mood from the normal programming, today was a play-through of laid back, chilled out sounds across a number of genres new to the show! Lay back, close your eyes, let it all wash over you, and enjoy a sonic cleansing!

shows.title: The rockier, somewhat psychedelic, 60s show!
shows.description: Having recently developed a mild yet healthy obsession for The Easybeats, today's show is a play-through of some of the more obscure 1960s rock, pop, and psychedelic songs of the decade.

shows.title: The rootsy, bluesy, heartland show!
shows.description: Inspired by a story about Springsteen's Rosalita being played to close out every party, today's show features a lot of brass and horns, a lot of guitars, and a lot of rock 'n roll. Think 1970s road trip, with a few songs thrown in from the next couple of decades. Wind the windows down, sit back in your seat, put your sunglasses on and munch those miles. Alternatively, dance your ass off in your kitchen. Listener's choice!

shows.title: The "ladies of pop, soul, and folk" show!
shows.description: Adrian Tongue has curated today's show focusing on the female persuasion. If you would like to join us in a wander through the music of women from the last 60 years or so, lend us your ears!

shows.title: The tentative toe-dip into cover versions show!
shows.description: It's a hard decision to play a cover version some times, and since doing the show, I'm finding myself falling in love with original versions of songs I've only known the covers of before. Today is a first pass at some of the cover versions that have been in my life, played after the originals. Not a competition, just a play-through and celebration of some great (in my opinion) music!

shows.title: The post-punk pop rock new wave show!
shows.description: Inspired by Joe Strummer's birthday, I picked some genre, vibe and era appropriate tunes to enjoy for the end of a WEEEEEK! If you're looking for some upbeat tunes to bop your head to and maybe even pogo around a little to, just press play!

shows.title: The gentle epics show!
shows.description: A selection of slower, mostly 70s and early 80s mellow, longer form tracks just creeping into the progressive rock genre in places, with some more well known "cookies" thrown in too.

shows.title: The catchy, poppy, hooky, rocky show!
shows.description: Inspired by a track from The Lost Boys soundtrack that I had waiting for a playlist, and a post from a friend with some new music from a new band quoted as saying "I'm a huge fan of heaviness surrounded by pop sensibilities and loads of vocal harmonies," today's show is all about that - melodic poppy, catchy, hooky rock!

shows.title: The even more new music show!
shows.description: A play-through of new music released in the last 6 weeks across a number of genres. Is the dream-pop genre (which is not my favourite) evolving into post dream-pop? It feels a little like that listening to some of these tracks, and some of them are sounding quite confidently 80s!

shows.title: The Stan’s heatwave tunes show!
shows.description: Nine year old Stanley Tongue has put together today’s playlist with some of his favourite songs from the 1960s to 1990s. There's some pop, rock, indie, alternative, punk, grunge, metal and some mellow. What were you listening to when you were 9??!

shows.title: The summer songs from the last seven decades show!
shows.description: It’s HOT today! So let’s sunbathe (and soundbathe) in some fun summer songs from the last sixty years - 1958 - 2018!

shows.title: The a day in the life of 1994 show!
shows.description: With Blur and Oasis at each others throats over chart supremacy - it was considered the great brit pop war, but what else was happening in 1994? If you are looking for a snapshot of popular music across a number of genres, there's only one way to find out!

shows.title: The "other" 1980s show!
shows.description: A little alternative, a little indie, some pop and some rock. Diverse, extravagant at times, and eclectic. This is a selection of some of the "other" music from the 1980s. Not hair metal, not power ballads, and not (as wonderful as it is) the bubblegum pop of the decade. What a weird and wonderful decade it was.

shows.title: The 1980s AOR show!
shows.description: A play-through of some less obvious, yet still popular album-oriented rock tracks from 1981 to 1991. Walking the fine line between Yacht Rock and Hair Metal there are some now underplayed gems in here from an era that just precedes the years I started to get into rock music - pre 1987!

shows.title: The sweltering Sunday summer show!
shows.description: It's blazing hot weather everywhere again, and today Dave Tongue has provided the playlist to accompany the BBQs, picnics, paddling pools, beers and garden cocktails. Up beat, fun songs to singalong to with a smile. These tunes aren't going to cool you down!

shows.title: The STAX summer soul songs to sweat to show!
shows.description: It's blazing hot weather everywhere today so to accompany the BBQs, picnics and garden cocktails, is a play-through of some of STAX's greatest up-tempo, funky soul hits with a little blues thrown in for good measure.

shows.title: The transatlantic alt and indie show!
shows.description: Some straightforward, fun enjoyable songs from both sides of the Atlantic that you don't have to think too hard about from the 90s. Nothing too obscure, nothing too challenging. A musical comfort blanket to swaddle yourself in!

shows.title: The 80s movie soundtrack show!
shows.description: Not the most obvious, but also not the most obscure selections from some of the greatest 80s movies of all time! Ghostbusters, Batman, The Goonies, Ferris Bueller's Day Off. That's just a teaser! Whip out your leg warmers, cut the fingers off your gloves, back comb your hair or else you're a Neo-Maxi Zoomdweebie!

shows.title: The mostly 90s alternative show!
shows.description: I woke up thinking about Concrete Blonde after listening to Bloodletting a few times in the car (on cassette) last week, and just wanted to enjoy some good old 90s alternative!

shows.title: The more new music show!
shows.description: A play-through of new music released in 2020. There's some "new releases" too, and a cheeky cover to start the show (released in 2020), but other than that - all new music from 2020.

shows.title: The little bit of everything show!
shows.description: Starting off gently with some acoustic indie/rock/pop before moving through some of the heavier late 60s psychedelic rock, into some 90s indie, some brand new music, and finally landing on another epic cover and guitar solo from Prince.

shows.title: The pot pourri of pop, part 2 show!
shows.description: Adrian Tongue has shared another expertly curated playlist of tracks, starting with some 60s pop, and moving through the genres and decades to end with some gentler rock and blues.

shows.title: The Phil's musical coming of age, part 4 show!
shows.description: Opening with some catch-up tracks from the 1970s, before rejoining the musical autobiography of Phil "Dr Philphy" Edwards in 1989. This is the fourth part of the story of growing up to music in England and picks up right after the Atom Spies split up.

shows.title: The musical theatre show!
shows.description: Something of a trip down memory lane with selections from my favourite musicals that I worked on or performed in at Playhouse on the Square in Memphis, TN. So many great songs to pick from, and so many more to still play out. Consider this Act 1 of this theme, with more to come!

shows.title: The muscle-car rock show!
shows.description: Inspired by an article I read on Tidal, this is the sound of early 1970s blues-based stadium hard rock. If your roof is down, and the road is open, this might be the show for you. Fire up that V8 and start munching miles!

shows.title: The female singer-songwriter show!
shows.description: I wouldn't stretch to calling this a Lilith Fair show (mainly for copyright reasons), but it is certainly a showcase of some of my favourite female singer-songwriters from the late 80s to present day - most of whom have played Lilith Fair! If that is a celebration of women in music, then I'm all for it!

shows.title: The not a theme, a seam, and a tribute to Peter Green show!
shows.description: From Ani DiFranco to Peter Green, with some legendary musicians in between. I followed a seam or a thread to get from Ani to Peter by way of Bob Dylan, Leonard Cohen, Phil Spector, The Beatles, Billy Preston, The Rolling Stones, the holy triumvirate of Eric Clapton, Jeff Beck and Jimmy Page, closing out with a selection of Peter Green's music with John Mayall, the Splinter Group and Fleetwood Mac.

shows.title: The Christmas in July show!
shows.description: This show does exactly what it says on the tin - all Christmas music, to celebrate Christmas in July. Make yourself a Christmas dinner, wrap up all your favourite things so you can open them yourself later, and watch Die Hard after you've listened with a glass of sherry!

shows.title: The guitar show, where the guitar doesn't steal the show show!
shows.description: I wanted to play the George Harrison While My Guitar Gently Weeps tribute with Prince's epic guitar solo, but I didn't want to make a show all about guitar solos, so loosely, this show listens to a variety of tracks with stand out guitar playing, without it being the instrument that steals the song. Most of the time!

shows.title: The two-tone, ska, ska-punk, pop and funk show!
shows.description: Bop around to some rocksteady beats on a journey through some of the most fun music of any genre.

shows.title: The new releases and from the vault show!
shows.description: A play-through of  new releases and new music across the rock, pop, and indie genres with a few twists as well as some "from the vaults" 1960s tracks.

shows.title: The little rock, little blues, little soul, little new show!
shows.description: A little bit of everything in the first show back from a break. Starting off with some rock, moving into some 60s pop and soul, then through some new music, some indie pop, and into a bluesy ending.

shows.title: The 100th show!
shows.description: Point Break Radio started on March 21st, 2020 as a way to stay connected with friends during lockdown. This show is dedicated to everyone who has listened and to everyone who has engaged. Thank you for being part of the conversation, and thank you for keeping me busy!

shows.title: The 60s pop with a soupçon of 70s show!
shows.description: Adrian Tongue has shared another expertly curated playlist of tracks, starting with some 60s pop, and moving through the genres to end with some deeps cuts from the psychedelic flower-power era.

shows.title: The 1998 show, Pt. 2!
shows.description: In contrast to part 1, this show is mostly deeper cuts, with some cookies included. It was a good summer, I was 18 years old and had just started at University, but there was a lot of popular music that I wasn't listening to. Today's show gives some of those tracks a second chance to fill the gaps in my musical consciousness.

shows.title: The new music show!
shows.description: A play-through of (mostly) all new music - the majority of it released in the last 6 weeks, including a previously unreleased track from The Rolling Stones!

shows.title: The live music festival show!
shows.description: A fantasy festival of live tracks through the decades with performances from Ben Folds, Counting Crows, U2, Aerosmith, The Rolling Stones, Bob Dylan, Joni Mitchell, Bob Marley, Otis Redding and more. All played non-stop, so close your eyes, hide your valuables in your tent, crack open a cider, and imagine you're there!

shows.title: The prolific contributors show, Pt. 2!
shows.description: A quintuple play-through of tracks produced by Bruce Fairbairn, Bob Rock, Mutt Lange, Jeff Lynne, and T Bone Burnett - names you may not be over-familiar with, but who have helped create some of my favourite music of the last 40 years.

shows.title: The laid-back alternative show!
shows.description: Indie rock, dream pop, new wave, and a whole host of other sub-genres that organise somewhat under the umbrella genre of "alternative" to help you unplug from the hurry.

shows.title: The chilled morning after vibes show!
shows.description: The day after Independence Day in the US, and the day after pubs re-opening day in the UK... If you need some morning after tunes that aren't too academic (and aren't too chilled either!) this one might be for you. ALSO! I got to premiere a track from a Leeds based band called SCUM. It's 42 seconds of pure joy, and so good I played it thrice!

shows.title: The singer-songwriter storyteller show!
shows.description: A selection of tracks that can take you on a journey musically and lyrically from the 1960s to early 2000s.

shows.title: The mostly mellow clean guitar tones show!
shows.description: A selection of laid back, but not lazy, songs from the 1960s to early 2000s. Songs you can sit back and sink into the chill of!

shows.title: The late 80s, early 90s rock show!
shows.description: This is the one I've been waiting for, but after getting into some "deeper cuts" with yesterday's show, and waking up with Aerosmith's Blind Man stuck in my head, I took a similar approach and didn't go for the obvious tracks. Lots of hair, lots of 'tude, a couple of ballads, and a sprinkling of innuendo, I really enjoyed this show. This is the music I grew up on!

shows.title: The Dave's faves 80 show!
shows.description: Dave Tongue curated a fantastic playlist for today's featuring lots of "cookies" and some great "spinners" too!

shows.title: The Northern Soul & Motown show - part 2!
shows.description: Adrian Tongue has shared another beautifully curated playlist of great tracks, starting off with some Northern Soul and moving through some 60s and 70s Soul and Motown. Perfect early evening vibes!

shows.title: The 1980's musical coming of age show - part 2!
shows.description: Opening with some fun and gentle post-punk, and then segueing into an expertly curated musical autobiography by Phil "Dr Philphy" Edwards. This is the second part of the story of being 16 years old in England in 1980 and growing up through the decade with Post-Punk, New Wave and John Peel, picking up in 1985 and closing out the decade.

shows.title: The road trip singalong show!
shows.description: A curated play-through perfectly suited for road trips, housework, workouts, bath time, gardening, cooking, working, studying, dancing, ironing, or having dinner. If you find it accompanying you on any other adventures, let me know and I'll add it to the list!

shows.title: The Wednesday wind down show!
shows.description: No strong theme today, but a fun play-through of some of my favourite tracks, and some of the new music and musicians I've discovered since doing the show. A little bit of 60s psychedelic pop/rock, some 90s power-pop, some blues, some funk, some theatrics from Frank Zappa, and some fantastic vocal performances from Joe Cocker, Jeff Buckley, Grace Slick, and Mavis Staples.

shows.title: The Steve Cropper show!
shows.description: As writer, musician, producer, and label owner, Steve Cropper has created some of the most well-known and well-loved music from the 1960s onwards. He's a Memphis legend, and while I lived there, I worked out of the same recording studio he owned after he left STAX – Trans-Maximus Records (TMI). Now owned by Playhouse on the Square, the building is still rich with creativity, and during my time there, we used the building for writing and recording music for numerous shows, and other projects.

shows.title: The road trips from your childhood show!
shows.description: Remember all the road trips you used to go on as a kid and the music you listened to, loved, and were even lulled to sleep by in the back of a car? This is a curated playlist put together by my friend Alex based on memories of road trips she took with her family in the 80s and 90s.

shows.title: The drum intros show!
shows.description: A not overly academic recognition of drummers across a variety of sub-genres of rock that have contributed to some of the most iconic few seconds (and more) of some of the best songs from the past 60 years.

shows.title: The laid back, chilled out show!
shows.description: Today's show was a play-through of mostly new music, but all a little more gentle on the spectrum.

shows.title: The little bit of everything show!
shows.description: Starting off with Vera Lynn, and moving into some blues rock, hip hop, classic 60s and 70s tunes as well as some more up to date brand new music from Bob Dylan and Larkin Poe.

shows.title: The colour in the title show!
shows.description: White, Gold, Silver, Blue, Red, Orange, Yellow, Green, Pink, Crimson, Purple, Grey, Brown, Black. Twice! Mum and David were inspired to create a playlist of songs with colours in the title which I trimmed into two hours. Some really fun tunes in there, and a different way of looking at (and listening to) the music.

shows.title: The birthday anything goes show!
shows.description: I'll be honest, Dave Tongue turned 40 today and all the plans became understandably unplanned. A curated show of anything goes, with more than a couple of drinks!

shows.title: The best upbeat British indie show!
shows.description: If you're looking for a time machine of tunes, or if you're out in the garden having a BBQ, a picnic, or catching some sun, this show might be the soundtrack for you.

shows.title: The soundbathing show!
shows.description: British DJ and TV presenter Johnny Vaughan coined the term "soundbathing" on his Radio X show, and I think it's such a perfect description for sinking into a song, and letting it all wash over you. Today's show should allow you to sit back, sink into your chair, turn the music up, and escape the world for a couple of hours. Oh, and there's some gin recipes in there too!

shows.title: The storytellers show!
shows.description: An eclectic curated list of artists, bands, and songs that tell a story. Either particularly poetic lyrics, or longer form storytelling in song.

shows.title: The metal (and more) show!
shows.description: Sometimes you don't know how much you need the healing power of music until you listen to two hours of metal and hard rock. A cathartic, escapist, strangely peaceful, sensorily overwhelming mix of music that's like a weighted blanket for your ears. Turn this one up loud, and tap your mood's main vein.

shows.title: The delta blues show!
shows.description: A double-play play-through of a selection of delta blues artists, with the unexpected discovery of a connection between Kurt Cobain, Paul Daniels, and Leadbelly.

shows.title: The 1980's musical coming of age show!
shows.description: Expertly curated by Phil "Dr Philphy" Edwards, this is the story of being 16 years old in England in 1980 and growing up through the decade with Post-Punk, New Wave and John Peel.

shows.title: The 1998 show!
shows.description: It was a good summer, I was 18 years old and had just started at University. New friends, new music, a new city, and the start of a new chapter. Today's show was a play through of chart hits in the UK from that year.

shows.title: The strawberry moon show!
shows.description: Today was full moon Friday (which I don't think is actually a thing), so I put together a selection of tracks from the 60s through to present day that either have moon in the title, or are related with some other lunar connection, which I realise all sounds rather hippieish ✌🏻

shows.title: The 70s(ish) rock and gentle prog show!
shows.description: Nerd out your weirdness with a selection of more gentle (by my standards) rock and progressive rock from the late 60s to early 80s.

shows.title: The Nile Rodgers show!
shows.description: Nile Rodgers has written, composed, produced, played (and been sampled on) some of the best music over the last five decades, and some of my all time favourite tracks. He's a true pop music superstar. Put on your dancing shoes for this one.

shows.title: The amplifying artists voices and civil rights/protest music show!
shows.description: With the protests and civil unrest surrounding the death of George Floyd, this show is a playback of some well known and lesser known civil rights songs and protest songs including music addressing civil rights in countries outside of the US.

shows.title: The potpourri of rock and pop through the decades show!
shows.description: Adrian Tongue shared a comprehensive playlist of great tracks that I manicured a little to fit today's show. From Genesis to George Harrison, from Marmalade to Marillion, there was a good diversity of music with a nice coherent flow.

shows.title: The postponed wedding party show!
shows.description: My friends Steve and Jen were going to be getting married today, but then... lockdown. This was the accompaniment to a remote wedding party to celebrate their special delay!

shows.title: The long distance, live bachelor party show!
shows.description: My friends Steve and Jen were due to get married tomorrow, but for the reasons we all know, it has been postponed. Tonight was the "stag do" (bachelor) party, so I did a little live show to accompany the zoom session.

shows.title: The 1970's musical coming of age show!
shows.description: Expertly curated by Phil "Dr Philphy" Edwards, this is the story of being 8 years old in England in 1972 and growing up through the decade discovering Glam, Punk, Post-Punk and New Wave.

shows.title: The not a sausage party show!
shows.description: A wander through the decades of rock, pop, and folk from the female perspective (or at least from the male perspective of the female contribution). Impossible to make this comprehensive, but this was a "first show" for a theme that will very likely have additional parts in the future.

shows.title: The break themed show!
shows.description: A selection of songs dedicated to metatarsal 5 in my left foot which I broke shortly after Sunday's show. Not a pity party, no gory details, just songs loosely linked to the theme of breaking something, falling, and being somewhat inconvenienced for a little while.

shows.title: The perfect beer garden, day drinking, summery, picnic show!
shows.description: A selection of some of the most  fun, upbeat, sing-a-long songs from in and around the 90s, expertly curated by Dave Tongue.

shows.title: The second half of the 1970s decade in music show!
shows.description: A meander through, and exploration of, number ones and other popular songs from 1976 to 1979. Today's show was primarily curated by Adrian Tongue.

shows.title: The road trip and summer sounds show!
shows.description: An earlier than normal start with an easy to pick list of well known, well loved songs across a number of decades. Not at all academic, but hopefully enjoyable. I had a lot of fun playing this one out.

shows.title: The power pop, rock, catchy hook show!
shows.description: Starting with some less obvious tracks from the 80s sleaze/glam/hair genres, and then moving through some power pop of the 70s, 80s, and 90s. Nothing too academic. Just some good fun songs!

shows.title: The selections from Rolling Stone's 500 greatest songs show!
shows.description: Lots of variety in the songs from Rolling Stone’s 500 greatest songs of all time list, as well as a few chosen by myself. Oh, and a child fell off its bike outside my house - don't worry, all was ok in the end.

shows.title: The rock(ier) show!
shows.description: This show started out as more of a mood than a theme, but it ended up being a showcase of new music throughout the genre. With new tracks from The Who, Pixies, Angels & Airwaves, Jimmy Eat World, and Alice Cooper - there was a lot (and more)!

shows.title: The show inspired by Dylan's famous "Judas!" gig!
shows.description: 54 years ago today, at the Manchester Free Trade Hall, before the final song of the night, an audience member yelled "Judas!" The rest is History. I played some songs from the few years before that event, and found a musical seam that brought us up to date with "new" music from the last 20 years.

shows.title: The show of many genres!
shows.description: I woke up thinking about the song Mother Mother by Tracy Bonham. That resulted in a journey through a number of genres that gets a little bit industrial, a little bit female vocalist, a little bit New Orleans Jazz, and a little bit 80s warrior pop.

shows.title: The lush, soft rock, smooth, 70s-ish show!
shows.description: Some less obvious songs from the era with luscious recordings, arrangements, and performances. I had a song in my head when I woke up, and started the whole playlist from there.

shows.title: The little bit indie, little bit alt show!
shows.description: Some fun tracks from a variety of artists, mainly 90s to present day. About 20 seconds into Biffy Clyro my computer crashed and hard restarted. I managed to get straight back on the air (within a minute or so) and recover the file after the show, stitching it together like nothing ever happened. 😎

shows.title: The mellow, but not melancholy show!
shows.description: Some brand new tracks from a variety of artists, as well as a couple of oldies. All listenable and interesting I think (hope)!

shows.title: The show for the final hours of the charity gaming marathon!
shows.description: Steve and Tim are raising money for the Macmillan Cancer Support as part of Macmillan Game Heroes. Today's show took them into their last two hours of 24 and across the finish line. Well done chaps!!

shows.title: The show for the charity gaming marathon!
shows.description: Steve and Tim are raising money for the Macmillan Cancer Support as part of Macmillan Game Heroes. Tonight's show took them into their 6th hour of 24.
